The paper discusses a model for predicting publication productivity of researchers based on their historical publication quantity and time. This topic falls under several sub-categories of computer science, including digital libraries (cs.DL), information retrieval (cs.IR), social and information networks (cs.SI), cryptography and security (cs.CR), and computers and society (cs.CY). However, given the focus on publication dynamics and productivity, cs.DL and cs.IR are the most likely sub-categories.
